226 
227 [Illustration] THE ELEMENTS OF GOOD TEA
228 
229 
230 This book is a sequel and a reply to a book by Stephen Graham,
231 explorer-poet, and Vernon Hill, artist.
232 
233 I had a splendid six weeks tramping with my lifetime friend, Stephen
234 Graham, in the Rockies. We climbed northwest through Glacier Park,
235 Montana, across the Canadian line into Alberta, Canada. There it is in
236 two sentences.
237 
238 It would take more than the _Encyclopædia Britannica_ to tell on how
239 many points I differ from Stephen, and on how many points I agree with
240 him. I had not the least idea that so much Lindsay was going into
241 Graham’s fireside notes--while I was asleep at noon, often recovering in
242 an hour from ten hours of restless, sleepless freezing by night. I do
243 not hold myself liable in court for any opinions of mine then recorded
244 by Graham. My daytime strength was not all given to thought, however,
245 but often to trying to keep Graham in sight when he was a quarter of a
246 mile ahead of me climbing mountains absolutely perpendicular. As I
247 remember our first fireside discussions, they were as to whether there
248 was actually such a person as Patrick Henry. Graham had an idea he was a
249 perverse invention of my own fancy. But he looked him up afterwards and
250 found there was such a man. As I remember our conversations after that
251 provocation, I kept trying to deliver to him from memory Bryce’s
252 _American Commonwealth_, unabridged, two volumes, one thousand pages
253 each. I remember those volumes well. I read every page in lonely country
254 hotels and on slow local trains while a Sunday field-worker for the
255 Anti-Saloon League. And now invisible leaves of Bryce often made the
256 chief ingredient of our tea. So I have indicated in the design.
257 
258 I did not tell Graham I was quoting the great ambassador, and so many
259 unsupported, heavy and formidable statements he quite properly hesitated
260 to write out, without further confirmation, though he drank them down
261 quite cheerfully. In the great blank spaces in Graham’s narrative where
262 he skips really splendid scenery, I was quoting Bryce--not always
263 singing hymns!
264 
265 The most authentic part of my book, the part Mr. Vernon Hill has left
266 out, is that the mountains were as steep as I have drawn them. His
267 mountains, otherwise quite correct, are not sufficiently perpendicular.
268 Vernon Hill, of course, was not physically with us on the expedition. He
269 was in London, drawing beautiful and famous Arcadian Calendars. When
270 later he came to illustrate Graham’s book in London, with Graham bending
271 over him, no one mentioned the fact that the mountains were all like
272 church steeples. Graham had not noticed it, and it did not occur to
273 Vernon Hill by wireless. Otherwise Vernon Hill was in excellent
274 communication with us, and every picture in Graham’s book expresses
275 exactly what Graham was talking to me about to make me forget the
276 tumbles and the briers, and to drown out the Bryce.
277 
278 After I had hunted for years and years to find an explorer-poet who
279 would take a long walk with me, and had scared every one off by the
280 elaborateness of the proposal, the first troubadour that took me up on
281 it almost broke my neck. It was a grand and awful time. The sensible
282 reviews of Graham’s book have been by Walter Prichard Eaton. He does not
283 discuss Graham’s opinions or mine. But he is very plain about the fact
284 that we almost slid into eternity. He has tried those mountains himself,
285 and he knows. He should write several more reviews.
286 
287 Stephen Graham is a lifetime friend, and I have assembled these drawings
288 as a sign thereof. But because I have been studying Hieroglyphics in the
289 Metropolitan Museum all this summer, and because United States
290 Hieroglyphics of my own invention are haunting me day and night, this
291 book is drawn, and not written. I serve notice on the critics--the
292 verses are most incidental, merely to explain the pictures. And so,
293 directly considered, it is much more a reply to Vernon Hill, the artist,
294 than to Stephen.
295 
296 The artist of the Arcadian Calendar discerned rightly. Graham and I
297 were in Arcady, even if it was a bit rough.
298 
299 Going-To-The-Sun Mountain is the very jewel of the mountains of Glacier
300 Park. All the tourists love it, and they are right. Its name fits it.
301 
302 Going-To-The-Sun Mountain is our American Fujiyama, as all testify who
303 have seen it.
304 
305 Obviously, an ingredient of good tea is talk on Egyptian Hieroglyphics.
306 I had an invisible copy of an Egyptian Grammar with me and I put a leaf
307 from it into every pot of tea. Graham did not take to the taste of it as
308 much as he did to the pages of Bryce, but he was nobly patient, as one
309 may say, with Egypt.
310 
311 The Hieroglyphics in this work are based on two more British-Egyptian
312 grammars he sent me after he reached London. Still, they may be
313 described as United States Hieroglyphics, and almost any Egyptologist
314 will be willing to describe them that way, having about as much to do
315 with Egypt as Egyptian cigarettes. The Egyptians were, briefly, a nation
316 of Vernon Hills, who drew their “Arcadian Calendar” for four thousand
317 years in red and black ink, or cut it in granite. _I keep thinking about
318 them!_ A free translation of the hieroglyphic inscription at the bottom
319 of the first picture following is:
320 
321 +-----------------------------------------------+
322 | _The beating heart of the waterfall of the |
323 | double truth, as it appears to a scribe, |
324 | a servant of Thoth--Thoth, who is god of |
325 | picture-writing, photoplays and hieroglyphics,|
326 | and an intense admirer of waterfalls._ |
327 +-----------------------------------------------+
328 
329 
330 With this start, the reader can go straight through the book without a
331 mistake.
332 
333 Now, a last word as to the seal, _The Elements of Good Tea_.
334 
335 On the southern side of the Canadian-United States boundary, just as we
336 reached it, our coffee gave out. Most symbolical happening! There in the
337 deep woods, as we passed to the northern side, Graham said with a sigh
338 of insatiable anticipation: “Now we will have some tea.” We had had tea
339 all along, alternated with coffee. But now Stephen, on his own heath,
340 was emphatic about it. So he made tea, a whole potful, with a kick like
341 a battering ram, and I drank my half.
342 
343 Certainly the most worth-while thing in Stephen’s book, and mine, is a
344 matter known to all men long before the books were written. That is,
345 that a Britisher and a United Stateser can cross the Canadian-American
346 line together and discover that it is hardly there; can discover that an
347 international boundary can be genuine and eternal and yet friendly. If
348 there is one thing on which Stephen and I will agree till the Judgment
349 Day, it is that all the boundaries in the world should be as open, and
350 as happy, as the Canadian-United States line. To many diplomats such a
351 boundary is incredible, and yet it exists, one of the longest in the
352 world.
353 
354 VACHEL LINDSAY
355 
