359 WE START WEST FOR THE WATERFALLS
360 
361 
362 Tricking us, making our hearts their prey,
363 The dreams of the dreams, with books of the dreams,
364 Haunt the homes of the town this day;
365 The visions of rivers, with rhymes of the waterfalls,
366 Haunt the yards of the town this day;
367 The fairies of the fairies, with the flowers of the fairies,
368 Haunt the factories of the town this day;
369 And we throw them kisses, and they fly away.
370 
371 Tricking us, making our hearts their prey,
372 The angels of the angels, with the flags of the angels,
373 Haunt the clouds above the town this day,
374 And we throw them kisses and they fly away.
375 And they call us west to the glacial mountains,
376 To the mines that are books, to the natural fountains.
377 
378 [Illustration]
379 
380 
381 
382 
383 GOING-TO-THE-SUN
384 
385 
386 The mountain peak called “Going-To-The-Sun,”
387 In Glacier Park,
388 Is the most gorgeous one,
389 And when the sun comes down to it, it glows
390 With emerald and rose.
391 
392 [Illustration]
393 
394 
395 
396 
397 THE MYSTIC ROOSTER OF THE MONTANA SUNRISE
398 
399 
400 On the mountain peak, called “Going-To-The-Sun,”
401 I saw the rooster that no storm can tame,
402 The center of the sun was but his eye,
403 His comb was but the sun rays and the flame.
404 There in the Glacier Park, above white glaciers,
405 There, above Montana and the west,
406 He crowed and called his boast around the world,
407 Emotion shook his red embroidered vest.
408 There is humor in the very biggest rooster,
409 But even more magnificence than fun.
410 I laugh because he acted like a rooster,
411 I am solemn, for he was the biggest one.
412 I like a rooster or a turkey gobbler,
413 I like their forthright impudence at times.
414 They are neither larks, nor trilling nightingales,
415 And yet they always sing in splendid rhymes.
416 When I heard the vast bird of the sunrise crying,
417 The world held not one inch of silly prose.
418 Any rooster is a flowerlike fowl,
419 And this one was a crimson Yankee rose.
420 
421 [Illustration]
422 
423 
424 
425 
426 THE BIRD CALLED “CURIOSITY”
427 
428 
429 Round the mountain peak called “Going-To-The-Sun,”
430 In Glacier Park, a steep and soaring one,
431 Circled a curious bird with pointed nose
432 Who led us on to every cave, and rose
433 And swept through every cloud, then brought us berries,
434 And all the acid gifts the mountain carries,
435 And let us guess which ones were good to eat.
436 And even when we slept his sharp wings beat
437 The weary fire, or shook the tree-top cones,
438 Or rattled dead twigs like a fairy’s bones.
439 The vulgar bird, “Curiosity”! When we
440 Were tired, and lean, and shaking at the knee,
441 We put this bird in harness. He was strong
442 As any ostrich, pulled our packs along,
443 Helped us up over the next annoying wall,
444 And dragged us to the chalet, and the tourists’ resting hall.
445 
446 And when once more we were young, well-fed men,
447 He beat the door to call us forth again.
448 
