544 
545 
546 THE PHEASANT SPEAKS OF HIS BIRTHDAYS
547 
548 
549 Up the good slope of Going-To-The-Sun,
550 I saw the Pheasant-Of-The-Sunrise fly.
551 Jewels in his feathers, mixed with dew.
552 Dew and jewels made his jeweled eye.
553 He paused to make a sonnet, which he sang,
554 Though nowhere else are pheasants sonneteers.
555 He emphasized with swooping and with skipping,
556 With winkings and intoxicated leers.
557 And how the bushes twinkled as he caroled:
558 
559 “Each morning is another birthday, friend.
560 And I have lived so many happy birthdays!
561 There are gifts with all the suns that here ascend!
562 Each bush, you see, has an unextinguished candle
563 And angel-food, and icing, and candy flowers,
564 And this long vine that climbs from earth to heaven
565 Gives me thoughts, and most erratic powers.
566 I eat its scarlet berries and its frosting.
567 If I choose, it is my present every day.
568 Then I can fly straight up to heaven’s doorstep
569 Following the green line all the way.
570 
571 [Illustration]
572 
573 “And then I tumble like a limber leaf
574 To my nest here, and another year is done
575 Or another thousand years, what does it matter
576 On the mountain peak called ‘Going-To-The-Sun’?”
577 
578 
579 
580 
581 THE MYSTIC UNICORN OF THE MONTANA SUNSET
582 
583 
584 On the mountain peak, called “Going-To-The-Sun,”
585 I saw the Unicorn-No-Storm-Can-Tame.
586 The center of the sun was but his eye,
587 His mane was but the sun rays and the flame.
588 There in that Glacier Park, above green pastures,
589 There above Stephen’s camp fire in the rocks,
590 He foamed and pawed and whinnied round the world,
591 His feathered sides and plumes and bristling locks
592 Seemed but the banners of a great announcement
593 That unicorns were spry as heretofore,
594 That not a camp fire of the world was dead,
595 That dragons lived in them, and thousands more
596 Camp-born, were clawing at the clouds of Asia,
597 Were rising with to-morrow’s dawn for men,
598 Camp-fire dragons, with the ancient unicorn
599 Bringing the Rosicrucian days again.
600 Any unicorn can drive away
601 Any thoughts the grown-up race has spoiled.
602 When I heard the Unicorn-of-Sunset ramping
603 New fancies in my veins bubbled and boiled.
604 
605 [Illustration]
606 
607 Any unicorn is worth his oats,
608 And so we fed him bacon, and we made
609 An extra cup of tea, which he drank.
610 Then he curled up coltwise, and in slumber sank.
611 Dragons sprang up, next day, where he had stayed.
612 They were in Fujiyama silks arrayed,
613 Or spoke of Everest to Stephen. Then began
614 Discussing the strange peak in Darien
615 That poets climb to see the Pacific well.
616 How Stephen climbed it later, I will let him tell.
617 Following the Unicorn-No-Storm-Can-Tame
618 Alone, in tropic woods, is a great game.
619 
620 
621 
622 
623 JOHNNY APPLESEED STILL FURTHER WEST
624 
625 
626 On the mountain peak, called “Going-To-The-Sun,”
627 I saw old Johnny Appleseed once more.
628 He ate an apple, threw away the core.
629 Then turned and smiled and slackly watched it fall
630 Into a crevice of the mountain wall.
631 In an instant there was an apple tree,
632 The roots split up the rocks beneath our feet,
633 And apples rolled down the green mountainside
634 And fairies popped from them, flying and free!
635 
636 [Illustration]
637 
638 And
639 Fairies
640 Came from them.
641 
642 [Illustration]
643 
644 
645 
646 
647 THE APPLE-BARREL OF JOHNNY APPLESEED
648 
649 
650 On the mountain peak, called “Going-To-The-Sun,”
651 I saw gray Johnny Appleseed at prayer
652 Just as the sunset made the old earth fair.
653 Then darkness came; in an instant, like great smoke,
654 The sun fell down as though its great hoops broke
655 And dark rich apples, poured from the dim flame
656 Where the sun set, came rolling toward the peak,
657 A storm of fruit, a mighty cider-reek,
658 The perfume of the orchards of the world,
659 From apple-shadows: red and russet domes
660 That turned to clouds of glory and strange homes
661 Above the mountain tops for cloud-born souls:--
662 Reproofs for men who build the world like moles,
663 Models for men, if they would build the world
664 As Johnny Appleseed would have it done--
665 Praying, and reading the books of Swedenborg
666 On the mountain top called “Going-To-The-Sun.”
667 
668 [Illustration]
669 
670 
671 
672 
673 THE COMET OF GOING-TO-THE-SUN
674 
675 
676 On the mountain peak, called “Going-To-The-Sun,”
677 A comet stopped to drink from a cool spring
678 And like a spirit-harp began to sing
679 To us, then hurried on to reach the sun.
680 We called him “Homer’s soul,” and “Milton’s wing.”
681 The harp-sound stayed, though he went up and on.
682 It turned to thunder, when he had quite gone--
683 And yet was like a soft voice of the sea,
684 And every whispering root and every blade of grass
685 And every tree
686 In the whole world, and brought thoughts of old songs
687 That blind men sang ten thousand years ago,
688 And all the springtime hearts of every nation know.
689 
690 [Illustration]
691 
692 
693 
694 
695 THE BOAT WITH THE KITE STRING AND THE CELESTIAL EYES
696 
697 
698 On the mountain peak, called “Going-To-The-Sun,”
699 I sat alone; while Stephen explored higher,
700 I dragged in sticks and logs and kept our fire.
701 
702 On soft-winged sails of meditation
703 My boat of spiral shells and flowers,
704 And fluffy clouds and twinkling hours,
705 My thought-boat went with the sun all day
706 Over the glaciers, far away.
707 I sat alone, but the chipmunks knew
708 My boat was high, and plain to view.
709 
710 I flew my ship like a kite. The thread
711 Was a cobweb silk, fine and thin,
712 That came from out the palm of my hand.
713 There I saw the ship begin.
714 From the gypsy’s life line thence it came
715 
716 A feather of mist that flew to the dawn,
717 And I felt the spool in my wrist unwind,
718 And I saw the feather on heaven’s lawn,
719 Now a glimmering ship like a lark awake.
720 And the kite string sang, but did not break.
721 
722 [Illustration]
723 
724 It stretched like the string of a violin
725 Played by invisible tides and waves.
726 It sang of Springfield yet to be.
727 It sang of the dead hours in their graves.
728 
729 And of the United States to be,
730 And of all the map stretched out below.
731 And my kite had pansy eyes in its wings,
732 And I saw the states in their bloom and glow
733 Yet a child’s block-map, and nothing more,
734 Flat patterns on a playroom floor.
735 
736 Texas the fort, by the river to the south,
737 Michigan a pheasant with a leaf in its mouth,
738 Illinois an ear of corn, in the shock,
739 Maine a moose-horn, gray as a rock.
740 California a whale, in gilded mail,
741 Montana, a ranch of alfalfa and clover,
742 
743 Montana with its mountain called “Going-To-The-Sun,”
744 An outdoor temple for the singer and the rover,
745 Wyoming a range for a summer lark,
746 With sparkling trails, and its Yellowstone Park,
747 Colorado an Indian tent for the world,
748 Where the smokes of care-free camps are curled,
749 Arizona a mission in the desert for all time,
750 Where the nerves find peace, and thoughts find rhyme,
751 New Mexico a clay pueblo full of dreams,
752 Eldorado in its valleys, ghosts by its streams.
753 Utah a throne for a grandeur unknown,
754 For haughty hearts, with ways of their own.
755 Nevada the cabin of Mark Twain in his youth,
756 Where he mined in the cañons, where he dug for the truth.
757 Washington a western soldier’s tent,
758 Idaho a chair for a president,
759 North and South Dakota, one buffalo hide,
760 Oregon a lumber mill on a mountain side,
761 Nebraska, Oklahoma, cowboy pistols pointing west
762 Kansas a wheat field where I, once, was a guest,
763 Iowa a corn pone sizzling hot,
764 Minnesota a farmer’s coffee-pot.
765 Arkansas a steamboat at Mark Twain’s door,
766 Missouri Mark Twain’s raft on the shore.
767 Louisiana a cavalier’s boot, just the thing
768 When we wade toward the mouth of the delta in the spring.
769 Mississippi a cotton scales,
770 Alabama many cotton bales,
771 Georgia a peach-basket red,
772 Florida a wild turkey’s head,
773 North Carolina a crane, flying through a cloud,
774 South Carolina a soldier, with head unbowed,
775 West Virginia, the raccoon, shrewd and slow,
776 Tennessee Bob Taylor’s fiddle and bow,
777 Virginia Thomas Jefferson’s mountain and shroud,
778 Kentucky the log cradle of the proud.
779 Maryland a plow, Delaware a pruning hook,
780 Indiana Riley’s Hoosier book,
781 Wisconsin a caldron, cool it who can,
782 Ohio Johnny Appleseed’s park for man.
783 Vermont a poet’s house, with waterfall and fern,
784 Where Frost writes songs that the world will learn.
785 
786 New Jersey the doorstep of the nation,
787 Pennsylvania the front room of the nation,
788 Where once Penn welcomed all creation
789 And let them sleep on the grassy floor
790 And let them eat the wild berries and explore.
791 Rhode Island, Roger Williams’ holy place,
792 Connecticut, an arbor of innocence and grace
793 Filled with flowers, and souls like lace,
794 Especially one little girl six years young
795 Who tells me stories in the fairy tongue.
796 
797 New Hampshire the mast of the Mayflower,
798 Massachusetts the prow of the Mayflower,
799 Most famous ark forevermore.
800 
801 The whole map a temple, if we patiently read,
802 With the statue of Liberty in majesty to plead
803 For Arcady to come once more,
804 And with New York on guard,
805 New York a sentinel,
806 New York a lion by the door.
807 
808 By my camp fire I grew older,
809 There were chipmunks on my shoulder,
810 While I saw the world,
811 With the eyes of my boat,
812 As one land,
813 With Asia and Alaska by the ice bound as one,
814 The Aurora Borealis was a cross bright as the sun.
815 I seemed to live through myriad days.
816 My eyes looked down like searching rays.
817 I took my flight over many races,
818 I saw, in my thought, all human faces.
819 And my spirit had its fill.
820 And the thread in my wrist wound in again
821 The cobweb shortened, strand on strand,
822 And my little ship came back to land
823 And was only a feather in my hand.
824 
825 
826 
827 
828 SO MUCH THE WORSE FOR BOSTON
829 
830 
831 [Sidenote:
832 
833 _Some words about singing this song,
834 Are written this border along._]
835 
836 I read the aspens like a book, and every leaf was signed,
837 And I climbed above the aspen-grove to read what I could find
838 On Mount Clinton, Colorado, I met a mountain-cat.
839 I will call him “Andrew Jackson,” and I mean no harm by that.
840 He was growling, and devouring a terrific mountain-rat.
841 But when the feast was ended, the mountain-cat was kind,
842 And showed a pretty smile, and spoke his mind.
843 “I am dreaming of old Boston,” he said, and wiped his jaws.
844 
845 [Illustration: THE BIG EARED RAT OF BOSTON]
846 
847 “I have often HEARD of Boston,” and he folded in his paws,
848 “Boston, Massachusetts, a mountain bold and great.
849 I will tell you all about it, if you care to curl and wait.
850 
851 [Sidenote:
852 
853 _If I cannot sing in the aspens’ tongue,
854 If I know not what they say,
855 Then I have never gone to school,
856 And have wasted all my day._]
857 
858 “In the Boston of my beauty-sleep, when storm-flowers are in bloom,
859 When storm-lilies and storm-thistles and storm-roses are in bloom,
860 The faithful cats go creeping through the catnip-ferns,
861 _And_ rainbows, _and_ sunshine, _and_ gloom,
862 And pounce upon the Boston Mice, that tremble underneath the flowers,
863 And pounce upon the big-eared rats, and drag them to the tomb.
864 For we are Tom-policemen, vigilant and sure.
865 We keep the Back Bay ditches and potato cellars pure.
866 Apples are not bitten into, cheese is let alone.
867 
868 [Illustration: VACHEL LINDSAY 1922
869 
870 THE BOSTON MOUSE WAITS IN TERROR OF THE MOUNTAIN-CAT, UNDER THE SHADOW
871 OF THE STORM-ROSE]
872 
873 [Sidenote:
874 
875 _Come, let us whisper of men and beasts
876 And joke as the aspens do,
877 And yet be solemn in their way,
878 And tell our thoughts
879 All summer through,
880 In the morning,
881 In the frost,
882 And in the midnight dew._]
883 
884 Sweet corn is left upon the cob, and the beef left on the bone.
885 Every Sunday morning, the Pilgrims give us codfish balls,
886 Because we keep the poisonous rats from the Boston halls.”
887 And then I contradicted him, in a manner firm and flat.
888 “I have never seen, in the famous Hub, suppression of the rat.”
889 “So much the worse for Boston,” said the whiskery mountain-cat.
890 
891 And the cat continued his great dream, closing one shrewd eye:
892 “The Tower-of-Babel Cactus blazes above the sky.
893 Fangs and sabers guard the buds and crimson fruits on high.
894 Yet cactus-eating eagles and black hawks hum through the air.
895 When the pigeons weep in Copley Square, look up, those wings are there,
896 
897 [Illustration: VACHEL LINDSAY 1922
898 
899 THE TOWER-OF-BABEL CACTUS BLAZES ABOVE THE SKY]
900 
901 [Sidenote:
902 
903 _The mountain-cat seems violent,
904 And of no good intent.
905 Yet read his words so gently
906 No bird will leave its tree,
907 No child will hate the simper or the noise
908 And hurry away from you and me.
909 Read like a meditative, catlike willow-tree._]
910 
911 [Sidenote:
912 
913 _Some words about singing this song,
914 Are scattered this border along._]
915 
916 Proud Yankee birds of prey, overshadowing the land,
917 Screaming to younger Yankees of the self-same brand,
918 Whose talk is like the American flag, snapping on the summit-pole,
919 Sky-rocket and star-spangled words, round sunflower words,
920 they use them whole.
921 There are no tailors in command, men seem like trees in honest leaves.
922 Their clothes are but their bark and hide, and sod and binding
923 for their sheaves.
924 Men are as the shocks of corn, as natural as alfalfa fields.
925 And no one yields to purse or badge; only to sweating manhood yields,
926 To natural authority, to wisdom straight from the new sun.
927 Who is the bull-god of the herd? The strongest and the shaggiest one.
928 Or if they preen at all, they preen with Walter Raleigh’s
929 gracious pride:--
930 The forest-ranger! One grand show! With gun and spade slung at his side!
931 Up on the dizzy timber-line, arbiter of life and fate,
932 Where sacred frost shines all the year, and freezing bee
933 and mossflower mate.
934 
935 [Sidenote:
936 
937 _Read like the Mariposa with the stately stem,
938 With green jade leaves like ripples and like waves,
939 And white jade petals,
940 Smooth as foam can be--
941 The Mariposa lily, that is leaning upon the young stream’s hem,
942 Speaking grandly to that larger flower
943 That grows down toward the sea, hour after hour
944 Hunting for the Pacific storms and caves._]
945 
946 “Boston is tough country, and the ranger rides with death,
947 Plunges to stop the forest fire against the black smoke’s breath,
948 Buries the cattle killed by eating larkspur lush and blue,
949 Shoots the calf-thieves, lumber-thieves, and gets train-robbers too.
950 
951 [Sidenote:
952 
953 _Some words about singing this song,
954 Are scattered this border along._]
955 
956 Governor and Sheriff obey his ordering hand,
957 Following his ostrich plume across the amber sand.
958 “But often, for lone days he goes, exploring cliffs afar,
959 And chants his King James’ Bible to tarantula and star.
960 I hear him read Egyptian tales, as he rides by in the dawn.
961 I am sometimes an Egyptian cat. My crudities are gone.
962 He spells, in Greek, that Homer, as he hurries on alone.
963 I hear him scan at Virgil, as I hide behind a stone.
964 “He had kept me fond of Hawthorne, and Thoreau, cold and wise.
965 The silvery waves of Walden Pond, gleam in a bobcat’s eyes.
966 He has taught us grateful beasts to sing, like Orpheus of old.
967 The Boston forest ranger brings back the Age of Gold.”
968 
969 And then I contradicted him, in a manner firm and flat.
970 
971 [Illustration: VACHEL LINDSAY 1922
972 
973 A BACK-BAY WHALE]
974 
975 “I have never heard, in the cultured Hub, of rowdy men like that.”
976 “So much the worse for Boston,” said the Rocky Mountain cat.
977 
978 [Sidenote:
979 
980 _Sing like the Mariposa to the stream that seeks the sea,
981 Speak like that flower,
982 With still,
983 Olympian jest,
984 And cuplike word
985 Filling the hour._]
986 
987 And the cat purred on, in his great dream, as one who
988 seeks the noblest ends:--
989 “Higher than the Back Bay whales, that spout and leap,
990 and bite their friends,
991 Higher than those Moby-Dicks, the Boston Lover’s trail ascends.
992 Higher than the Methodist, or Unitarian spire,
993 Beyond the range of any fence of bowlder or barbed wire,
994 Telling to each other what the Boston Boys have done,
995 The lodge-pole pines go towering to the timber-line and sun.
996 And their whisper stirs love’s fury in each pantherish girl-child,
997 Till she dresses like a columbine, or a bleeding heart gone wild.
998 Like a harebell, golden aster, bluebell, Indian arrow,
999 Blue jay, squirrel, meadow lark, loco, mountain sparrow.
1000 Mayflower, sagebrush, dying swan, they court in disarray.
1001 The masquerade, in Love’s hot name, is like a forest-play.
1002 And she is held in worship who adores the noblest boys.
1003 So miner-lovers bring her new amazing pets and toys.
1004 Mewing, prowling hunters bring her grizzlies in chains.
1005 Ranchers bring red apples through the silver rains.
1006 In the mountain of my beauty-sleep, when storm-flowers
1007 Are in bloom,
1008 The Boston of my beauty-sleep, when storm-flowers
1009 Are in bloom.
1010 There are just such naked waterfalls, as are roaring there below.
1011 For the springs of Boston Common are from priceless summer snow.
1012 Serene the wind-cleared Boston peaks, and there white rabbits run
1013 Like funny giant snowflakes, hopping in the sun.
1014 The ptarmigan will leap and fly and clutter through the drift
1015 And the baby ptarmigans ‘peep, peep,’ when the weasel eyelids lift.
1016 And where the pools are still and deep, dwarf willows see themselves,
1017 And the Boston Mariposas bend, like mirror-kissing elves.
1018 White is the gypsum cliff, and white the snowbird’s warm,
1019 deep-feathered home,
1020 White are the cottonwood and birch, white is the fountain-foam.
1021 
1022 “In the waterfalls from the sunburnt cliffs, the bold
1023 nymphs leap and shriek
1024 The wrath of the water makes them fight, its kisses make them weak.
1025 
1026 With shoulders hot with sunburn, with bodies rose and white,
1027 And streaming curls like sunrise rays, or curls like flags of night,
1028 Flowing to their dancing feet, circling them in storm,
1029 And their adorers glory in each lean, Ionic form.
1030 Oh, the hearts of women, then set free. They live the life of old
1031 That chickadees and bobcats sing, the famous Age of Gold....
1032 They sleep and star-gaze on the grass, their red-ore camp fires shine,
1033 Like heaps of unset rubies spilled on velvet superfine.
1034 And love of man and maid is when the granite weds the snow-white stream.
1035 The ranch house bursts with babies. In the wood-lot deep eyes gleam,
1036 Buffalo children, barking wolves, fuming cinnamon bears.
1037 Human mustangs kick the paint from the breakfast-table chairs.”
1038 
1039 And then I contradicted him, in a manner firm and flat.
1040 “I have never heard, in the modest Hub, of a stock ill-bred as that.”
1041 “So much the worse for Boston,” said the lecherous mountain-cat.
1042 
1043 And the cat continued with the dream, as the snow blew round in drifts.
1044 “The caves beneath the craggy sides of Boston hold tremendous gifts
1045 For many youths that enter there, and lift up every stone that lifts.
1046 They wander in, and wander on, finding all new things they can,
1047 Some forms of jade or chrysoprase, more rare than radium for man.
1048 And the burro trains, to fetch the loot, are jolly fool parades.
1049 The burros flap their ears and bray, and take the steepest grades.
1050 Or loaded with long mining-drills, and railroad rails,
1051 and boards for flumes,
1052 Up Beacon Hill with fossil bats, swine bones from geologic tombs,
1053 Or loaded with cliff-mummies of lost dwellers of the land.
1054 Explorers’ yells and bridle bells sound above the sand.
1055 
1056 “In the desert of my beauty-sleep, when rainflowers
1057 Will not bloom,
1058 In the Boston of my beauty-sleep, when storms
1059 Will not bloom,
1060 
1061 [Illustration: VACHEL LINDSAY 1922
1062 
1063 THE BAT]
1064 
1065 By Bunker Hill’s tall obelisk, till the August sun awakes,
1066 I brood and stalk blue shadows, and my mad heart breaks.
1067 Thoughts of a hunt unutterable ring the obelisk around.
1068 And a thousand glorious sphinxes spring, singing, from the ground.
1069 Very white young Salem witches ride them down the west.
1070 The gravel makes a flat, lone track, the eye has endless rest.
1071 Fair girls and beasts charge, dreaming, through the
1072 salt-sand white as snow,
1073 Hunting the three-toed pony, while mysterious slaughters flow.
1074 And the bat from the salt desert sucks the clouds on high
1075 Until they fall in ashes, and all the sky is dry.
1076 Oh, the empty Spanish Missions, where the bells ring without hand,
1077 As we drive the shadowy dinosaurs and mammoths through the sand.”
1078 
1079 And then I contradicted him, in a manner firm and flat.
1080 “I have never seen, in the sun-kissed Hub, circuses like that.”
1081 “So much the worse for you, my cub,” said the slant-eyed mountain-cat.
1082 
1083 And the cat continued with his yarn, while I stood there marveling:--
1084 “I here proclaim that I am not a vague, an abstract thing.
1085 I like to eat the turkey-leg, the lamb, the chickenwing.
1086 Yet the cat that knows not fasting, the cat that knows not dream,
1087 That has not drunk dim mammoth-blood from the long-dead desert stream,
1088 That has not rolled in the alkali-encrusted pits of bones
1089 By the saber-toothed white tiger’s cave, where he kicked
1090 the ancient stones,
1091 Has not known sacred Boston. Our gods are burning ore.
1092 Our Colorado gods are the stars of heaven’s floor.
1093 But the god of Massachusetts is a Tiger they adore.
1094 
1095 “From that saber-tooth’s ghost-purring goes the whispered word of power
1096 In the sunset, in the moonlight, in the purple sunrise hour:--
1097 That an Indian chief is born, in a teepee, to the west,
1098 That a school of rattlesnakes is rattling, on the mountain’s breast,
1099 That an opal has been grubbed from the ground by a mole,
1100 That a bumble-bee has found a new way to save his soul.
1101 In Egyptian granite Boston, the rumor has gone round
1102 That new ways to tame the whirlwind have been marvelously found.
1103 That a Balanced Rock has fallen, that a battle has been won
1104 In the soul of some young touch-me-not, some tigerish Emerson.”
1105 
1106 And then I contradicted him, in a manner firm and flat.
1107 “Boston people do not read their Emerson like that.”
1108 “So much the worse for Boston,” said the self-reliant cat.
1109 Then I saw the cat there towering, like a cat cut from a hill:--
1110 A prophet-beast of Nature’s law, staring with stony will,
1111 Pacing on the icy top, then stretched in drowsy thought,
1112 Then, listening, on tiptoe, to the voice the snowwind brought,
1113 Tearing at the fire-killed pine trees, kittenish again,
1114 Then speaking like a lion, long made president of men:--
1115 “There are such holy plains and streams, there are such
1116 sky-arched spaces,
1117 There are life-long trails for private lives, and endless
1118 whispering places.
1119 Range is so wide there is not room for lust and poison breath
1120 And flesh may walk in Eden, forgetting shame and death.”
1121 
1122 And then I contradicted him, in a manner firm and flat.
1123 “I have never heard, in Boston, of anything like that.”
1124 “_Boston is peculiar._
1125 _Boston is mysterious._
1126 _You do not know your Boston_,” said the wise, fastidious cat,
1127 And turned again to lick the skull of his prey, the mountain-rat!
1128 And at that, he broke off his wild dream of a perfect human race.
1129 And I walked down to the aspen grove where is neither time nor place,
1130 Nor measurement, nor space, except that grass has room
1131 And aspen leaves whisper on forever in their grace.
1132 All day they watch along the banks. All night the perfume goes
1133 From the Mariposa’s chalice to the marble mountain-rose,
1134 In the Boston of their beauty-sleep, when storm-flowers
1135 Are in bloom,
1136 In the mystery of their beauty-sleep, when storm-flowers
1137 Are in bloom.
1138 
1139 [Illustration: ROCKETS ON THE WAY TO SATURN]
1140 
1141 
1142 
1143 
1144 THE ROCKETS THAT REACHED SATURN
1145 
1146 
1147 On the Fourth of July sky rockets went up
1148 Over the church and the trees and the town,
1149 Stripes and stars, riding red cars.
1150 Each rocket wore a red-white-and-blue gown,
1151 And I did not see one rocket come down.
1152 
1153 Next day on the hill I found dead sticks,
1154 Scorched like blown-out candle-wicks.
1155 
1156 But where are the rockets? Up in the sky.
1157 As for the sticks, let them lie.
1158 Dead sticks are not the Fourth of July.
1159 
1160 In Saturn they grow like wonderful weeds,
1161 In some ways like weeds of ours,
1162 Twisted and beautiful, straight and awry,
1163 But nodding all day to the heavenly powers.
1164 The stalks are smoke,
1165 And the blossoms green light,
1166 And crystalline fireworks flowers.
1167 
1168 [Illustration: VACHEL LINDSAY 1922
1169 
1170 ROCKETS IN SATURN]
1171 
1172 
1173 
1174 
1175 MEDITATION
1176 
1177 
1178 A spirit in soft slippers
1179 Walked the Gulf Stream floor.
1180 She opened many a cabin door
1181 Of ships a long time underseas.
1182 She read long-rest Egyptian books
1183 And looked upon skull-faces,
1184 And read their restless looks
1185 Shining through the shadows
1186 Of phosphorescent streaming waves,--
1187 Impatient for the Judgment horn
1188 To lift them from their purple graves.
1189 
1190 [Illustration]
1191 
1192 
1193 
1194 
1195 THE TRAVELER
1196 
1197 
1198 The Moon’s a devil-jester
1199 Who makes himself too free.
1200 The rascal is not always
1201 Where he appears to be:--
1202 Sometimes he is in my heart--
1203 Sometimes in the sea.
1204 Then tides are in my heart,
1205 And tides are in the sea.
1206 O traveler! abiding not
1207 Where he pretends to be!
1208 
1209 [Illustration: THE MOON IS A DEVIL-JESTER
1210 
1211 VACHEL LINDSAY 1922]
1212 
1213 
1214 
1215 
1216 ELIZABETH BARRETT BROWNING
1217 
1218 
1219 Elizabeth Barrett Browning
1220 Sat gossiping with Robert.
1221 (She was really a raving beauty in her day.
1222 With Mary Pickford curls in clouds and whirls.)
1223 She was trying to think of something nice to say,
1224 So she pointed to a page by her fellow star and sage,
1225 And said: “I wish that _I_ could write that way!”
1226 
1227 [Illustration]
1228 
1229 
1230 
1231 
1232 SOME BALLOONS GROW ON TREES
1233 
1234 FOR BETSY RICHARDS
1235 
1236 
1237 Some balloons grow on trees,
1238 On rubber trees, indeed.
1239 You plant old rubber-boots for seed.
1240 
1241 Some balloons grow on trees.
1242 If you want them red,
1243 You pour red ink into the boots,
1244 There in the balloon bed,
1245 
1246 And blue ink if you want them blue.
1247 But if you desire them green,
1248 Just let it pass.
1249 They will turn green to match the grass.
1250 
1251 Some balloons grow on trees.
1252 And if you do not spray them soon
1253 With water-pots of hellebore
1254 You will not have
1255 One ripe balloon.
1256 Mosquitoes will bite them in the night
1257 Explode them like a thunder-storm
1258 And give the town a fright.
1259 
1260 [Illustration]
1261 
1262 Some balloons grow on trees.
1263 If they grow too fast
1264 And are not gathered every day
1265 The infants stand aghast
1266 To see them tear up by the roots
1267 The trees on which they grew
1268 And scatter dirt on the front walk
1269 And disappear from view
1270 Into the blue.
1271 
1272 
1273 
1274 
1275 BABYLON’S GARDENS ARE BURNING
1276 
1277 
1278 There, on the shores of the river Euphrates,
1279 Babylon’s gardens are burning this morning.
1280 Prophets warned,
1281 Prophets prophesied,
1282 But no one in Babylon heeded the warning.
1283 
1284 [Illustration: BABYLON’S GARDENS ARE BURNING
1285 
1286 VACHEL LINDSAY 1922]
1287 
1288 [Illustration]
1289 
1290 
1291 
1292 
1293 IN THE BEAUTY PARLORS
1294 
1295 
1296 A jumbo so vain, and fond of his shape
1297 Had himself beautified by a gray ape,
1298 Tattooed and gilded with elegant signs,
1299 The latest and merriest monkey designs.
1300 Then the ape rode the jumbo
1301 And made the land gape,
1302 As he sat at his ease in the elephant chair.
1303 He had tattooed himself with designs from a shawl,
1304 And he gathered a grape with a self-possessed air,
1305 And threw down a twig at another fine ape.
1306 
1307 [Illustration: VACHEL LINDSAY 1922
1308 
1309 THE APE RODE THE JUMBO]
1310 
1311 [Illustration]
1312 
1313 
1314 
1315 
1316 A POLITICAL CAMPAIGN
1317 
1318 
1319 A duck within the harem of a drake who ran for president
1320 Swam in his parade, and made it an event.
1321 She carried a big card of his footprints and she said:--
1322 “He waddles like an arrow, straight ahead.”
1323 
1324 [Illustration]
1325 
1326 
1327 
1328 
1329 OLD JUDGE HOOT OWL
1330 
1331 
1332 Old Judge Hoot Owl sits by his inkwell
1333 Writing wills for the wealthy and swell.
1334 He knows something he won’t tell.
1335 Three little house flies, drowned in his inkwell.
1336 Three little scandals in a peanut shell.
1337 
